film screening&discussion mirror mirror and in harm's way events at stanford film screening&discussion mirror mirror and in harm's way facebook twitter email print add to calendar reknown filmmaker jan krawitz will screen and discuss two films as part of the winter quarter events for ms at 40 and the future of feminism mirror mirror provocatively explores the relationship between a woman's body image and the quest for an idealized female form blending humor and candor the film incisively illuminates the vagaries in the concept of an ideal body type in harm's way is a haunting memoir that explores how the experiences of adulthood both defy and reinforce the lessons of childhood prompted by her adult experience as a random victim of sexual assault the filmmaker revisits childhood's fragile myths to examine a belief system gone awry free and open to all jan krawitz documentary filmmaker and director mfa program in documentary film and video stanford university professor in department of art & art history school of humanities & sciences jan krawitz has been independently producing documentary films for thirty years her work has been exhibited and awarded at film festivals in the united states and abroad among them sundance nyon edinburgh margaret mead london sydney full frame south by southwest sxsw ann arbor and the new york film festival when monday february 27 2012 7 00 pm where stanford women's community center map audience general public faculty staff students alumni friends members tags arts other humanities film sponsor feminist studies contact 650 723 7685 fmstadmin gmail com permalink http events stanford edu events 303 30391 more info last modified february 22 2012
